docs.abstract: Cutting-edge innovations are set to upend some of the constants of growing old.
docs.snippet: Cutting-edge innovations are set to upend some of the constants of growing old.
docs.lead_paragraph: Welcoming a robot into her family was never Maxine Duncan’s idea of a support aide in her older years. But this winter, she and her partner, Herbert Yarbrough, signed up to test a telepresence robot in their retirement community, the Heritage Downtown, in Walnut Creek, Calif. Their new pal has a screen for a head and scuttles around on wheels. The lure was being able to connect more easily with their families via video calls.

docs.abstract: Amazon’s “Z: The Beginning of Everything,” about Zelda and F. Scott Fitzgerald, depicts the couple’s early years, though without much sizzle.
docs.snippet: Amazon’s “Z: The Beginning of Everything,” about Zelda and F. Scott Fitzgerald, depicts the couple’s early years, though without much sizzle.
docs.lead_paragraph: Perhaps the kindest way to look at the Amazon series “Z: The Beginning of Everything” is as a brave example of revisionist history. Any college English major knows that Zelda and F. Scott Fitzgerald were one of the liveliest literary couples ever, right? And the flapper era was a blizzard of energy and saucy fun, wasn’t it? Well, this series, which arrives Friday on Amazon, makes both the Fitzgeralds and the 1920s seem drab as dishwater.

headline.main: Review: ‘Z,’ Hardly the Last Word on the Fitzgeralds

docs.abstract: Sears, as well as other longtime retailers, are struggling because of the Amazon juggernaut.
docs.snippet: Sears, as well as other longtime retailers, are struggling because of the Amazon juggernaut.
docs.lead_paragraph: The Sears Holdings Corporation, which is projected to lose more than $2 billion this year, is in the retailing dead pool. As its prospects for a turnaround appear to grow dimmer, it may seem to be another morality tale for bricks-and-mortar retailers in the age of Amazon.

headline.main: Sears Clings to Catalog Thinking in an Online World
headline.print_headline: Sears Sells Something for Everyone. And That’s the Problem.

docs.abstract: The business would mesh nicely with the e-commerce giant, while the acquisition would show that Silicon Valley supports efforts to keep jobs at home.
docs.snippet: The business would mesh nicely with the e-commerce giant, while the acquisition would show that Silicon Valley supports efforts to keep jobs at home.
docs.lead_paragraph: In the retail-store slump, Jeff Bezos may be holding a Trump card. Amazon.com, the e-commerce giant he runs, is considering a bid for the bankrupt American Apparel, according to a Reuters exclusive, just as Macy’s and other department stores are losing sales and cutting staff. A deal could be a handy way to show a president-elect suspicious of Silicon Valley that thousands of working-class jobs are being saved.

headline.main: American Apparel Could Bolster Amazon’s Standing With Trump

docs.abstract: In this Amazon series, Giovanni Ribisi stars as an ex-con passing himself off as the long-lost grandson of a clan that runs a bail-bond shop. Bryan Cranston plays his nemesis.
docs.snippet: In this Amazon series, Giovanni Ribisi stars as an ex-con passing himself off as the long-lost grandson of a clan that runs a bail-bond shop. Bryan Cranston plays his nemesis.
docs.lead_paragraph: At some point during the year and a half since Amazon first posted the pilot of “Sneaky Pete,” an appealing new series available on Friday, a few changes crept into the episode. It’s hard to pinpoint them all, because the original pilot isn’t around for comparison. But the scene in which the famously rare bourbon Pappy Van Winkle is drunk out of paper cups is definitely new.

headline.main: Review: Con Man Poses as Long-Lost Grandson in ‘Sneaky Pete’
headline.print_headline: Worming His Way Into the Bosom of a Family

docs.abstract: The dystopian novel, published in 1949, about tyranny and the suppression of critical thought, has found a fresh audience in the United States.
docs.snippet: The dystopian novel, published in 1949, about tyranny and the suppression of critical thought, has found a fresh audience in the United States.
docs.lead_paragraph: George Orwell’s classic book “1984,” about a dystopian future where critical thought is suppressed under a totalitarian regime, has seen a surge in sales this month, rising to the top of the Amazon best-seller list in the United States and leading its publisher to have tens of thousands of new copies printed.

headline.main: George Orwell’s ‘1984’ Is Suddenly a Best-Seller
headline.print_headline: George Orwell’s ‘1984’ Has a Sales Surge
